pth interviews, Averett examines the reasons why these parents choose to homeschool, from those who disagree with sex education and LGBT content in schools, to others who want to protect their children’s sexual and gender identities. With eye-opening detail, she shows us how homeschooling is a trend being chosen by an increasingly diverse subset of American families, at times in order to empower—or constrain—children’s gender and sexuality. Ultimately, Averett explores how homeschooling, as a growing practice, has changed the roles that families, schools, and the state play in children’s lives. As teachers, parents, and policymakers debate the future of public education, The Homeschool Choice sheds light on the ongoing struggle over school choice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identity in educationzUnited States. 0aHome schoolingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPrivatization in educationzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Home Schooling.2bisacsh  aAptitudes.  aAttachment parenting.  aBorn this way.  aChild welfare.  aChildhood.  aClass.  aCritiques of public schools.  aDeskilling of teaching profession.  aEducation reform.  aEducation.  aGender inequality.  aGender.  aGendered division of labor.  aGiftedness.  aGovernment inefficiency.  aHeteronormativity.  aHomeschool instruction.  aHomeschooling regulation.  aHomeschooling regulations.  aIdeologies of childhood.  aIndividuality.  aInequality.  aIntensive motherhood.  aIntensive mothering.  aLGBTQ youth.  aMotherhood.  aNeoliberal motherhood.  aNeoliberalism.  aParenting.  aProgressive education reform.  aRace.  aReligious right.  aResearch methods.  aSchool Choice.  aSchool funding.  aSex education.  aSexuality.  aSpecial needs.  aStandardized testing.  aTemperaments.  aTex